Hi friends =F0=9F=91=8B,
Happy Friday and welcome back to our 55th Weekly Dose of Optimism.
Hope everyone=E2=80=99s caught their breath after last week. It looks like =
LK-99 is more likely than not some sort of cool magnet and not a room-tempe=
rature superconductor, although the National Physics Lab New Delhi posted a=
 promising replication attempt [ https://twitter.com/floates0x/status/16896=
38120739033089?s=3D20 ] yesterday. Manifold has replication at 14% [ https:=
//manifold.markets/QuantumObserver/will-the-lk99-room-temp-ambient-pre ].=
=20
It=E2=80=99s most likely so over, but we=E2=80=99ve got stories that should=
 bring your optimism so back.=20
Let=E2=80=99s get to it.
The Weekly Dose is brought to you by=E2=80=A6 Tegus [ https://www.tegus.com=
/free-trial?utm_medium=3Dnewsletter&utm_source=3Dnotboring&utm_campaign=3Dn=
ot-boring ]
Have you ever spent hours of time evaluating investment opportunities only =
to discover that your data isn=E2=80=99t reliable?
Tegus [ https://www.tegus.com/free-trial?utm_medium=3Dnewsletter&utm_source=
=3Dnotboring&utm_campaign=3Dnot-boring ] unites insights from credible expe=
rts with the best financial data to give you more powerful perspectives for=
 your investment decisions. With top-notch quality across expert calls, tra=
nscripts, financial models, and easy-to-cite SEC data, you can gain a uniqu=
e perspective and ultimately make bold, high-yield investment decisions.
(1) US scientists repeat fusion ignition breakthrough for 2nd time [ https:=
//www.reuters.com/business/energy/us-scientists-repeat-fusion-power-breakth=
rough-ft-2023-08-06/ ]
From Reuters
U.S. scientists have achieved net energy gain in a fusion reaction for the =
second time since December, the Lawrence Livermore National Laboratory said=
 on Sunday.
Scientists at the California-based lab repeated the fusion ignition breakth=
rough in an experiment in the National Ignition Facility (NIF) on July 30 t=
hat produced a higher energy yield than in December.
If the last few weeks have taught us anything, it=E2=80=99s that replicatio=
n and repeatability are important! Back in December, the Lawrence Livermore=
 National Laboratory made history with the first ever net energy gain fusio=
n ignition event. Now, the lab has produced a second net energy gain  in a =
fusion experiment, this time with a higher energy yield. Another =E2=80=9CQ=
>1=E2=80=9D reaction.
=E2=80=9CQ>1=E2=80=9D occurs when more energy is produced by a reaction tha=
n was input into it. While Q>1 experiments are important, there are still s=
ignificant hurdles in scaling and commercializing nuclear fusion as a sourc=
e of energy. But if we=E2=80=99re able to overcome those hurdles and scale =
nuclear fusion, energy will be cheap and infinitely abundant, leading to fu=
rther breakthrough technologies, energy security, climate solutions, and ma=
jor quality of life improvements. It=E2=80=99s one of those technological a=
dvancements that unlocks a whole wave of further advancements.=20
(2) Semaglutide 2.4 mg reduces the risk of major adverse cardiovascular eve=
nts [ https://www.novonordisk.com/news-and-media/news-and-ir-materials/news=
-details.html?id=3D166301 ]
From Novo Nordisk
The trial achieved its primary objective by demonstrating a statistically s=
ignificant and superior reduction in MACE of 20% for people treated with se=
maglutide 2.4 mg compared to placebo.
Over the past couple of months, the public perception of Semaglutide seems =
to have shifted a bit. Is it effective long-term? Is it actually net-net go=
od for you? Is it good for society to have a =E2=80=9Cmagic drug=E2=80=9D l=
ike this to solve your problems?
I think the jury is still out on each of those questions. Our view is that =
for a certain percentage of the population, weight-loss medication is reall=
y their only viable option for losing weight and improving overall health o=
utcomes. They=E2=80=99ve tried everything =E2=80=94 dieting, exercise, life=
style changes =E2=80=94 but nothing seems to work. They=E2=80=99re likely s=
uffering from an addiction or psychological condition that makes organic lo=
ng-term weight-loss excruciatingly hard. For these folks, semaglutide is a =
godsend.
And, according to new research from Novo Nordisk, the maker of semaglutide,=
 the drug also reduces the risk of a major adverse cardiovascular event by =
nearly 20%. This is a particularly important finding for obese people, who =
have an increased risk of cardiovascular disease, but no medication that wa=
s both effective in weight management while also reducing the likelihood of=
 a MACE.
(3) Ancient mud cracks on Mars point to conditions favorable for life [ htt=
ps://www.science.org/content/article/ancient-mud-cracks-mars-point-conditio=
ns-favorable-life ]
Phie Jacobs for Nature
The discovery of distinctive mud cracks on Mar=E2=80=99s surface suggest an=
cient Mars cycled through sustained wet and dry seasons for millions of yea=
rs. Not only would the climate have been habitable, scientists say, but the=
 cycling might have also given the basic chemistry of life a boost.
A new report, published yesterday in  [ https://www.nature.com/articles/s41=
586-023-06220-3 ]Nature [ https://www.nature.com/articles/s41586-023-06220-=
3 ], contains compelling evidence for an Earth-like climate on early Mars. =
The Curiosity rover on Mars discovered hexagon-shaped cracks in ancient roc=
ks on Mars, that add to mounting evidence that Mars once had a warm climate=
 with a wet-dry cycle.
So why is this important or relevant?
Mars=E2=80=99 warm climate may have been conducive to life formation
Understanding how life on Mars may have originated could give us a better u=
nderstanding of how life originates in general
Just another reminder of how vast the universe is. We barely know anything =
about Mars, our solar system neighbor =E2=80=94 maybe it had life, maybe it=
 didn=E2=80=99t we just don=E2=80=99t know. What else don=E2=80=99t we know=
 about the rest of our vast universe?=20
(4) Joscha Bach: Life, Intelligence, Consciousness, AI & the Future of Huma=
ns [ https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=3De8qJsk1j2zE ]
Ideally, you want to, I think, build agents that play the longest possible =
games. The longest possible games is to keep entropy at bay as long as poss=
ible, by doing interesting stuff.
Packy here. I tweeted the other day that I like the Lex Fridman podcast [ h=
ttps://twitter.com/packyM/status/1689298139772014593?s=3D20 ], an oddly con=
troversial take. This conversation with German artificial intelligence rese=
archer and cognitive scientist Joscha Bach [ https://twitter.com/Plinz ] is=
 what triggered it.=20
Joscha brought the heat, touching on everything from AI to transcendence to=
 panpsychism with a mix of logic, scientific rigor, and openness to the wis=
dom of old ideas.=20
One idea that particularly tickled my brain was that AGI is going to be sub=
strate agnostic: it won=E2=80=99t just run on silicon, but on anything that=
 can compute, including the biosphere, our bodies, and our brains. If that=
=E2=80=99s the case, instead of AI killing us all, we all connect into a gl=
obal =E2=80=9Calmost holographic brain.=E2=80=9D=20
It sounds bizarre and high-kid when I say it, but decidedly less so in the =
flow of the conversation and coming from Bach=E2=80=99s precise German-acce=
nted voice, so just give it a listen. It=E2=80=99s brainwormed me.=20
(5) Musk's Neuralink raises $280 mln in funding led by Thiel's Founders Fun=
d [ https://www.reuters.com/technology/musks-neuralink-raises-280-mln-lates=
t-fundraise-2023-08-07/ ]
From Reuters
But justttt in case AGI can=E2=80=99t figure out how to connect directly wi=
th our brain, there=E2=80=99s Neuralink. The brain-computer interface (BCI)=
 company founded by Elon Musk recently raised a mega $280M Series D led by =
Founders Fund. The company aims to connect the human brain with computers, =
which could have a range of potential applications from medical treatments =
to enhancing human cognition. The best overview of the company (unsurprisin=
gly) comes from Tim Urban in his 2017 piece =E2=80=9CNeuralink and the Brai=
n=E2=80=99s Magical Future. [ https://waitbutwhy.com/2017/04/neuralink.html=
 ]=E2=80=9D
The round comes just months after the company received FDA approval for its=
 first in-human clinical trial. Neuralink will implant thin electrode threa=
ds into the brain to read and influence neural activity. These threads inte=
rface with a chip that processes, transmits, and receives data, allowing fo=
r communication between the brain and external devices. A quadriplegic Neur=
alink patient may, for example, be able to move a cursor and click on a scr=
een only using her thoughts. Neuralink=E2=80=99s starting with medical use-=
cases first, but where this goes in the long-term gets even wilder=E2=80=A6=
imagine having instantaneous access to all knowledge on the internet, or Ch=
atGPT 10, embedded directly in your brain.=20
Bonus: Understanding Lasso and Jolt, from theory to code [ http://Understan=
ding Lasso and Jolt, from theory to code ]
By Sam Ragsdale, Michael Zhu, and Justin Thaler at a16z crypto
Our initial implementation provides roughly=C2=A0a 10x speedup [ https://gi=
thub.com/a16z/Lasso/blob/master/src/benches/m1_16gb_parallel_benches.log ]=
=C2=A0over the lookup argument in the popular, well- engineered=C2=A0halo2 =
[ https://github.com/privacy-scaling-explorations/halo2 ]=C2=A0toolchain; w=
e expect improvements of around 40x when optimizations are complete.=C2=A0
Packy again. If you remember back to the piece I wrote about Aleo [ https:/=
/www.notboring.co/p/aleo-can-you-keep-a-secret ] last December, about 10k w=
ords in (you remember, right?), I talked about one of the biggest issues fa=
cing the zero-knowledge [ https://www.notboring.co/p/zero-knowledge ] space=
: proving zkSNARKs is still really slow.=20
Yesterday, my friends at a16z crypto (disclosure: I=E2=80=99m an advisor th=
ere) released a pair of open-source projects, Lasso and Jolt, that provide =
three main benefits:=20
Faster performance
More accessible developer experience
Easier auditability
If you want to read the details, they=E2=80=99re all in the post [ http://U=
nderstanding Lasso and Jolt, from theory to code ], plus an even deeper one=
 [ https://a16zcrypto.com/posts/article/introducing-lasso-and-jolt/ ] from =
zk savant Justin Thaler. The takeaway is that Lasso and Jolt should acceler=
ate the adoption of zero-knowledge proofs, make blockchains more scalable, =
and help =E2=80=9Celiminate a major trade-off inherent in living, working, =
and transacting online: the convenience, speed, reach, and scale of the int=
ernet in exchange for our privacy.=E2=80=9D
